The code computes the transfer function T(ell) = sqrt(P_recon(ell) / P_truth(ell)) to evaluate the spectral fidelity of the trained Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE). 1. Data and Model Loading: It loads the validation dataset split and initializes the UNet model with the weights saved from Step 2. 2. Inference: For each validation patch, the model predicts the tSZ map. The prediction is scaled back by 10^-6 to match the original dimensionless Compton-y units. 3. Power Spectrum Calculation: The auto-power spectra of both the predicted and ground-truth maps are computed using utils.powers. A Tukey/Hann window (window_alpha=0.5) is applied to mitigate edge effects caused by the non-periodic nature of the flat-sky patches. The pixel size is set to 1.17 arcmin. 4. Transfer Function: The transfer function T(ell) is calculated for each patch. The mean and standard deviation across all validation patches are then computed. 5. Metrics and Plotting: A scalar summary metric (the mean T(ell) in the range 3000 < ell < 8000) is printed to the console. A diagnostic plot is generated, displaying the mean T(ell) with +/- 1 sigma error bands, and clearly highlighting the ell > 5000 regime where baryonic feedback signatures are most prominent. The results are saved to disk.

